snippet.textDisplay: I'd like to touch on the point about land use, mainly that a lot of land allocated to livestock is not suitable for crops because it's too barren and without nutrients, so just gets used for grazing. Taking animals out of the equation isn't necessarily going to allow plants to make up the food demand as the land used for those animals can't be reallocated for crop fields. These include places like cattle driving stations in Australia, desert ranches in states like Arizona or Texas and even grasslands in Europe which would quickly become overgrown and uninhabitable without animals to keep it short.
snippet.textOriginal: I'd like to touch on the point about land use, mainly that a lot of land allocated to livestock is not suitable for crops because it's too barren and without nutrients, so just gets used for grazing. Taking animals out of the equation isn't necessarily going to allow plants to make up the food demand as the land used for those animals can't be reallocated for crop fields. These include places like cattle driving stations in Australia, desert ranches in states like Arizona or Texas and even grasslands in Europe which would quickly become overgrown and uninhabitable without animals to keep it short.

That said, I'll keep an open mind and look forward to future developments. Well done Mr. Rober!

snippet.textDisplay:
Mark, I want to thank you so much for talking about this in a way so many have neglected to. Beyond and Impossible have become so large and in demand recently it is good to take a step back and look at the real benefit to such innovation.
As somebody who has been vegetarian for a very large portion of my life I have been so insanely excited to see the advances in meat alternatives for my personal consumption, but also as an avid vocalist regarding climate change I am even more excited to see prominent figures such as Bill Gates saying these advancements have the potential to make an observable positive impact on our planet.
